<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-380-230  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 380 230.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  March 1990 v63 n3 p48(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>For COCOM nations, consensus is hard to come by. (the CoordinationCommittee for Multilateral Export Control must ease restrictionsto allow greater electronics industry exports to Eastern Europe)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shandle, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Coordination Committee for Multilateral Export Control (COCOM)is the central international agency coordinating restrictions onexport of strategic technologies to Eastern Europe, but neitherCOCOM nor member governments, such as the US, find it easy toreach consensus on what products should and should not be shippedEast.andP;  COCOM members implement COCOM agreements independently, andthere are no formal sanctions for breaching the COCOM agreements.andO;The market opportunities arising from the opening of EasternEurope have motivated trade missions from COCOM nations, and thereis pressure by COCOM members to decontrol commodities availableoff-the-self in the West.andP;  Other COCOM members doubt the abilityof Eastern Europe nations to prevent such products from being sentonwards to the Soviet Union.andP;  The US's Secretary of CommerceRobert A. Mosbacher favors relaxation of restrictions.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Trade and Professional AssociationsEuropeRegulationTrendsMarket EntryCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsInternational trade.andO;Person:    Mosbacher, Robert A. (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>